{"questionId":"22154988","questionHtml":"<p>explain why <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>α</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi>α</mi></mfenced><mo> </mo><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi>α</mi></mfenced></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>(Because matrix multiplication represents the composition of transformations) two rotations of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi></math> are equivalent to a rotation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>α</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>so the two matrices are equal (so each of the entries are also equal)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>α</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>cos</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi>α</mi></mfenced><mo> </mo><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi>α</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22154988","referenceCode":"24M.1.AHL.TZ1.11ci","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"explain why sin 2α=2 sin α cos α.","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","AHL 5.14—Setting up a DE, solve by separating variables","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.8—Unit circle, Pythag identity, solving trig equations graphically","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.9—Matrix transformations"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}